The '''Berkeley Forum''', commonly referred to simply as '''"the Forum"''', is a [[student organization]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], founded in 2012. It is a non-partisan organization that hosts debates, panels, and talks with distinguished speakers on various topics. The Forum is modeled after similar organizations at other prestigious universities, like the [[Oxford Union]], the [[Cambridge Union Society]], the [[Yale Political Union]], and the [https://forum.iop.harvard.edu/ John F. Kennedy Jr. Forum].<ref name="Daily Cal 1">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2013/03/06/berkeley-forum-hosts-panel-featuring-robert-reich-and-romney-campaign-policy-director/ |title=Robert Reich, former Romney campaign policy director debate federal budget on campus |publisher=The Daily Californian |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name="History">{{cite web|url=http://forum.berkeley.edu/history |title=History |publisher=The Berkeley Forum |accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzfeed.com/kimberlywang/this-uc-berkeley-student-is-running-the-most-ambitious-stude |title= This UC Berkeley Student Is Running The Most Elaborate Student Body Presidential Campaign |publisher=BuzzFeed |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>
The Forum's events typically feature speeches by the speakers, followed by question and answer sessions with the audience. Tickets for [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]] students, faculty, and staff are always free, while tickets for the general public are free or are available for a small fee.<ref name="About Us">{{cite web|url=http://forum.berkeley.edu/aboutus |title=About Us |publisher=The Berkeley Forum |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

== Notable past events ==

The Berkeley Forum's first event was a panel debate on the federal fiscal crisis, held in March 2013. The panel featured former [[Secretary of Labor]] [[Robert Reich]], policy director of the [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|2012 Romney presidential campaign]] [[Lanhee Chen]], and the Dean of the [[Goldman School of Public Policy]] Henry Brady.<ref name="Daily Cal 1" />

In November 2013, the Forum hosted [[Creative Commons]] co-founder and [[United States|American]] [[academic]] and [[political activist]], [[Lawrence Lessig]]. Lessig discussed the role of money in politics, in a speech entitled "Corrupting the Vote."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2013/11/11/berkeley-forum-hosts-lawrence-lessig-talk-money-politics/ |title= Berkeley Forum hosts Lawrence Lessig talk on money in politics |publisher=The Daily Californian |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>
The Forum's largest and most noteworthy event to date was a speech given by [[Kentucky]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Rand Paul]] on March 19, 2014. Senator Paul talked about the issue of government surveillance programs, like that of the [[National Security Agency|NSA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/politics/article/Republican-Rand-Paul-fires-up-a-Berkeley-crowd-5332740.php |title=Republican Rand Paul fires up a Berkeley crowd |publisher=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2014/03/19/rand-paul-gop-like-bad-pizza-crust/ |title=Rand Paul: GOP like bad pizza crust |publisher= CNN |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/peter-watts/bluffed-baffled-rand-paul-berkeley_b_5000062.html |title= Bluffed, Baffled and Bewildered: How Rand Paul Bilked Berkeley |publisher= The Huffington Post |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rand-paul-criticizes-obama-others-over-spying |title=Rand Paul Criticizes Obama, Others Over Spying |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/19/nation/la-na-rand-paul-berkeley-20140320 |title= Sen. Rand Paul takes his anti-spying message to UC Berkeley |publisher= Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/03/20/rand-paul-criticizes-obama-others-over-spying/ |title= Rand Paul rebukes Obama over spying in Berkeley speech |publisher= Fox News |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> The event was held at [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]] Auditorium at [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley's]] [[International House Berkeley|International House]] with approximately 400 people in attendance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2014/03/19/rand-paul-discusses-domestic-spying-berkeley-forum-event/ |title=Rand Paul discusses domestic spying and privacy rights at Berkeley Forum event |publisher=The Daily Californian |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> Notable attendees include former [[Secretary of Labor]] [[Robert Reich]] and [[Lieutenant Governor of California]] [[Gavin Newsom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/news/ci_25378185/republican-presidential-hopeful-rand-paul-finds-plenty-support |title=Rand Paul, Republican presidential hopeful, finds support in Berkeley, of all places |publisher=Mercury News |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> The next day, the event was featured on the front page of [[The New York Times]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.admissions.berkeley.edu/2014/04/guest-blog-sergey-mann/ |title=Guest Blog: The Story of One of the Best Decisions of My Life |publisher= UC Berkeley Office of Undergraduate Admissions |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/20/us/politics/rand-paul-speaks-at-berkeley.html?_r=0 |title=Rand Paul, Warning About Spying, Faults Obama |publisher= The New York Times |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>
In March 2014, the Berkeley Forum also hosted former [[United States Secretary of Energy|US Secretary of Energy]] and [[List of Nobel laureates|Nobel Laureate]] [[Steven Chu]]. Chu spoke about sustainable energy options.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2014/03/31/steven-chu-former-secretary-energy-discusses-sustainable-energy-options/ |title= Steven Chu, former US Secretary of Energy, discusses sustainable energy options |publisher= The Daily Californian |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>

On November 14, 2014, the Berkeley Forum hosted [[Oakland,_California|Oakland]] mayor [[Jean Quan]]. Quan spoke about local government and inequality in American cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.berkeley.edu/Jean-Quan |title= An Address by Jean Quan |publisher=The Berkeley Forum |accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref> Then, on December 10, the Forum hosted American entrepreneur and venture capitalist, [[Peter Thiel]]. The event was interrupted by protesters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/peter-thiel-chased-off-stage-by-angry-protestors-at-uc-berkeley-2014-12 |title= Billionaire Investor Peter Thiel Chased Off Stage By Angry Protesters At UC Berkeley |publisher=Business Insider |accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2014/12/11/protestors-disrupt-peter-thiel/ |title=A little too much disruption for Peter Thiel, Silicon Valley's iconoclast-in-chief |publisher=Fortune |accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.berkeley.edu/peter-thiel-statement.html |title=A Statement Regarding the Peter Thiel Address |publisher=The Berkeley Forum |accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref>
